justification:
Campagna, which was more than likely named after the designer, Angelo Testa's friend, Paul Campagna, epitomizes Testa’s design vocabulary.&amp;nbsp; The work was designed around 1950 for Knoll Associates, and utilizes Testa’s preferred linear and geometric forms, which were likely associated with his Bauhaus training. The hard edges of the concentric rectangles in this textile, however, have been softened by their appearance of being almost hand-drawn. He made variations of this design, three of which are in the Museum’s collection: 1948-119-5, 2002 -14-2, and 2002-14-3, and are also titled Campagna. However, the pattern of 1948-119-5 differs slightly as it consists of only six large blocks that have multiple concentric rectangles within each block.&amp;nbsp; 
&amp;nbsp;
This particular textile is one of the most well known works designed by Testa, and was published in many architecture and design journals of the day. It is indicative of his innovative work as one of the leading American textile designers of the 1940s and 1950s, and represents an important moment in post-war America when textiles were a very calculated part of every modern interior.
